rd_1.jpg\" alt=\"Latitude lines\" width=\"50%\">\n","\n","*Darker red means higher imperiled biodiversity; green area is the protected land; Credit: [New York Times](https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2022/03/03/climate/biodiversity-map.html)*\n","\n","**In this project, you will:**\n","- **Identify census designated places** (metropolitan areas) that had the largest percent of population growth from 2010 to 2020 and investigate if they are in the close proximity to a biodiversity imperiled areas.\n","- **Determine the [EPA Level IV ecoregions](https://www.epa.gov/eco-research/level-iii-and-iv-ecoregions-continental-united-states)** which have the highest biodiversity importance for imperiled species.\n","- **Create meaningful cartographic visualization** of your results."],"metadata":{"id":"wSKdjvddh9O0"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **Core Datasets**\n","\n","- [2024 NatureServe Map of Biodiversity Importance](https://natureserve.maps.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=5ad6e1b3b6fb48bbad92d903114c9f28)\n","- [EPA Level IV ecoregions](https://www.epa.gov/eco-research/level-iii-and-iv-ecoregions-continental-united-states)\n","- [U.S. Census TIGER Boundaries for census designated places or metropolitan areas](https://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/geo/tiger-line-file.html)\n","- [U.S. Census Population Data](https://www.census.gov/topics/population.html)"],"metadata":{"id":"DXjWL9YsrAsW"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **Expected Outcomes**\n","\n","1. A cleaned dataset of metropolitan areas in the continental U.S. which may include the following fields:\n","    - GEOID\n","    - County names\n","    - State names\n","    - Metropolitan area name\n","    - Populations (2010, 2020)\n","    - Percent population change 2010-2020\n","    - Highest biodiversity importance in the area\n","    - Median biodiversity importance in the area\n","    - Lowest biodiversity importance in the area\n","    - Variance of biodiversity importance inside the area\n","    - Rank of median biodiversity importance inside the area\n","2. A cleaned dataset of EPA level IV ecoregions which may include the following fields:\n","    - Ecoregion name\n","    - Highest biodiversity importance inside the area\n","    - Average biodiversity importance inside the area\n","    - Median biodiversity importance inside the area\n","    - Variance of biodiversity importance inside the area\n","    - Rank of median biodiversity importance inside the area\n","2. A series of maps which use appropriate visual variables (color, size, symbolization, etc.) to showcase the fastest-growing metropolitan area boundaries, their relationships to the most imperiled EPA level IV ecoregions, and those ecoregions' biodiversity importance.\n","3. A final report describing the spatial patterns observed and analyzing the findings for their significance."],"metadata":{"id":"OShv0SybsVOk"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **Visualization Examples**\n","\n","<img src=\"https://static01.nyt.com/newsgraphics/2022/02/15/biodiversity-usa/02880a81902bd053d0545f8e3be097ba287c91f8/big_map_protected-Artboard-xl.jpg\" width=\"60%\">\n","\n","*Note: Green areas reflect federal, state and local biodiversity protections.*\n","*Credit: [New York Times](https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2022/03/03/climate/biodiversity-map.html)*"],"metadata":{"id":"r0SXHq1xwnsa"}}]}